#   When both --quiet and --json are used, --json takes precedence.
#
#   In JSON mode:
#   - All normal output becomes structured JSON on stdout.
#   - Errors and warnings are converted to JSON error objects.
#   - This mode is stronger than plain --quiet.
#
#   JSON Output Rules (MUST be followed):
#   - Always output valid JSON on stdout (never stderr for JSON mode).
#   - Use "type" field to indicate message category.
#   - Keep structure consistent and flat where possible.
#   - Include "message" for human-readable text when appropriate.
#   - For status/list commands, use arrays/objects for structured data.
#   - Errors must use type: "error" with optional "code".
